04825nam a22006735i 9780231546836DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315468367 a10.7312/de-c186782doi  a(DE-B1597)502914  a(OCoLC)1047608376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM480b.C743 2018eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a303.309422300aCritical Theory at a Crossroads :bConversations on Resistance in Times of Crisis /ced. by Stijn De Cauwer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Resistance in Times of Crisis -- t1. A Critical Europe Can Do It! -- t2. We Should be Modest, When It Comes to the Designation of the Possible Subjects of a New Politics -- t3. The History of the Notion of Crisis -- t4. Neoliberalism Against the Promise of Modernity -- t5. The European Union Is a Cage -- t6. We Need to Have a Clear Alternative -- t7. Finance Is an Extractive Sector -- t8. How to Think a War Machine? -- t9. The Creativity Dispositive: Labor Reform by Stealth -- t10. The Idea of Crisis -- t11. Terror and the Rejection of Sense -- t12. Community in Crisis -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are living in an age of crisis—or an age in which everything is labeled a crisis. Financial, debt, and refugee “crises” have erupted. The word has also been applied to the Arab Spring and its aftermath, Brexit, the 2016 U.S. election, and many other international events. Yet the term has contradictory political and strategic meanings for those challenging power structures and those seeking to preserve them. For critics of the status quo, can the rhetoric of crisis be used to foment urgency around issues like climate change and financialization, or does framing a situation as a “crisis” play into the hands of the existing political order, which then seeks to tighten the leash by creating a state of emergency?Critical Theory at a Crossroads presents conversations with prominent theorists about the crises that have marked the past years, the protest movements that have risen up in response, and the use of the term in political discourse. Tariq Ali, Rosi Braidotti, Wendy Brown, Maurizio Lazzarato, Angela McRobbie, Jean-Luc Nancy, Antonio Negri, Jacques Rancière, Saskia Sassen, and Joseph Vogl offer their views on contemporary challenges and how we might address them, candidly discussing the alternatives that new social movements have offered, alongside an exchange between Zygmunt Bauman and Roberto Esposito on theories of community. Sparring over crucial developments in these past years of catastrophe and the calamity of everyday life under capitalism, they shed light on how crises and the discourse of crisis can both obscure and reveal fundamental aspects of modern societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCritical theory. 0aPolitical participationzEurope. 0aPower (Social sciences)zEurope. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aAli, Tariq.1 aBauman, Zygmunt.1 aBraidotti, Rosi.1 aBrown, Wendy.1 aCauwer, Stijn De, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Cauwer, Stijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsposito, Roberto.1 aLazzarato, Maurizio.1 aMcRobbie, Angela.1 aNancy, Jean-Luc.1 aNegri, Antonio.1 aRancière, Jacques.1 aSassen, Saskia.1 aVogl, Joseph.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/de-c1867840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546836423Coveruhttps